This shortage of clear cut legislation, curbs the woman’s freedom of choice; there is usually the voluntary balance of access and risk. Yet for the majority of women in many communities and cultures in Southeast Asia, the only option for terminating pregnancy is illegal abortion (Chun & Lui 1989).

Illegal within community borders or informal ‘outside law’ highly destructive methods including the insertion of objects into the cervix, pouring of caustic chemicals and electrical shock (Chapman 1988). The resultant intrauterine burns, lacerations and perforations lead to massive hemorrhage and institutional dead at rates exceeding 50%.

National data for Taiwan suggest that approximately 1 in 13 women experiencing pregnancy complications present at a health facility, where 10- 15% of the babies were either stillborn or died in the first week of life. These data indicate that approximately 100,000 abortions and 80,000 post abortion infractions occur each year.
